<HEADLINE> EDS: Adds Details hke101029--Nepal Deputy Speaker Resigns in Parliament Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Deputy Speaker Lila
Subba Shrestha resigned Saturday to avoid the humiliation of
forced resignation as well as to show her party's resolve to force
the rival speaker out of office.
</P>
<P>
She made the announcement while chairing a Lower House session
to discuss a motion tabled by the opposition against Speaker Ram
Chandra Poudel.
</P>
<P>
The house was also scheduled to discuss a tit-for-tat motion
against her tabled by the ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation started in early September over the
controversial Local Autonomy Bill, into which the main opposition
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) sought
but failed to add a provision that automatically terminates one's
post if a local elected official defects to another party.
</P>
<P>
The party fears that without the provision, thousands of
local-level party workers may defect to its rival group, the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML), which broke
away from it in March this year and joined the government in
August.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML, on the other hand, wanted to get the bill passed
without the provision in order to win over more workers for the
next general elections due by November 1999.
</P>
<P>
Most of the mayors, deputy mayors, district development
committee chairmen, vice chairmen and members elected from the
CPN-UML during the local elections in May and July last year had
joined the CPN-ML.
</P>
<P>
More local elected officials are said to be willing to join the
CPN-ML, but were waiting for the Local Autonomy Bill to be passed
by parliament.
</P>
<P>
The bill has been pushed through both houses of parliament and
presented to the king for approval.
</P>
<P>
Prior to its passage in the Lower House of parliament on
September 17, the bill met strong opposition from the opposition
MPs. But when the MPs were voicing protest, Speaker Poudel
conducted voice voting on the bill and declared that it had been
passed in the house.
</P>
<P>
Manhandling between MPs of the ruling and opposition parties
ensued. And on September 23, 54 MPs from the CPN-UML and the
National Democratic Party (RPP, Thapa) registered a motion at the
Parliament Secretariat, accusing Poudel who is from the ruling
Nepali Congress (NC) of partisan conduct.
</P>
<P>
The NC and its ruling partner CPN-ML registered the same day a
tit-for-tat motion against Deputy Speaker Shrestha from the
CPN-UML.
</P>
<P>
Announcing that it would not accept the bill, the CPN-UML
refused to compromise and withdraw its motion, and demanded
replaying of the tape recording of the house proceedings on
September 17.
</P>
<P>
The tape was played Friday in the presence of MPs at the
Parliament Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The NC and CPN-ML said the tape showed the allegation of the
opposition was baseless as there was no procedural mistake.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML still refused to accept it, accusing the speaker
and the government of tampering with the tape overnight.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, it issued a whip requiring all of its 49 MPs to
participate in the discussion on the motion and vote for it.
</P>
<P>
But well aware that the deputy speaker is sure to lose her seat
as it cannot muster a two-third majority in the 205-member Lower
House to defeat the motion against her, the CPN-UML directed her
to quit to avoid the humiliation of forced resignation.
</P>
<P>
Speaker Poudel had announced that he would not resign as the
ruling parties have at least 137 seats in the house to guarantee
his clinging to power.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML had threatened to make its lawmakers resign en
masse as an ultimate measure. However, this does not necessarily
mean the end of the majority government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
