<HEADLINE> Bioinvasion Threatens Biological Diversity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Bioinvasion, the spread of
exotic species, has become a great threat to world biological
diversity, the Worldwatch Institute, an environmental organization
based here, said Saturday in its study.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in the institute, Chris Bright,
author of the report entitled "Life of Bounds: bioinvasion in a
borderless world," said that compared to living things, chemical
spills are inert, they cannot reproduce and they tend to dissipate
over time. But when an exotic species establishes a beachhead, it
can proliferate over time and spread to new areas. It can also
adapt -- it tends to get better and better at exploiting an area's
resources, and at suppressing native species.
</P>
<P>
Natural boundaries like mountains, deserts, and ocean currents
used to isolate one ecosystem from another. But trade, travel, and
other human activities are moving more and more organisms around
these boundaries, touching off more and more invasions, said the
study.
</P>
<P>
Bright said that exotics can now be found in most of the
Earth's lake and river systems, along most coastlines, on
virtually all major islands, and scattered throughout all of the
continents including Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
Bioinvasion may lead social menace in several ways. In 1991 for
example, epidemic cholera returned to the Americas, probably via
contaminated ship ballast water released into a Peruvian harbor.
An Atlantic jellyfish provoked the collapse of the fisheries in
the Black Sea. The water hyacinth from South America has done the
same thing in Africa's Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The author said people round the world should take action to
protect the native species from the bioinvasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
