<HEADLINE> Tsohatzopoulos: Military Action Will Be Eventually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said Saturday that he was optimistic that a NATO
military intervention in Kosovo would be averted even at the last
minute.
</P>
<P>
He said that decisions reached to date concerned the completion
of military preparations with a view to exerting pressure for a
political solution.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed optimism that logic would prevail before
the final political decision was made for the conversion of such
preparations into military action.
</P>
<P>
While advising coolheadedness, he said that the critical time
limit for any further developments would be early next week.
</P>
<P>
Greece said Friday that it would not use its right to veto if
NATO decided to militarily intervene in Kosovo, but it would not
send troops and airplanes to take part in any military strike.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos stressed that those who lived thousands of
kilometers away would not see any of the results of a military
strike, but Greece would be directly affected by the
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
He added that Greece was continuing efforts to help find a
peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis because a military
intervention would have no positive outcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
