<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls on Teachers to End Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi Saturday appealed to teachers nationwide to call off their
October 12.
</P>
<P>
He announced that he "will not accept to be pressurized" to
negotiate with striking teachers who demand that the government
implement its pledges of the 150-200 pay rise for teachers.
</P>
<P>
It was "unrealistic" to force the government to negotiate on
the teachers' pay dispute as the economy could not accommodate it
at the moment, Moi said at the Moi Day celebrations marking his
20-year rule.
</P>
<P>
Once the economy had recovered, salaries of the entire public
service including those of teachers will be reviewed, Moi said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the 250,000-member Kenya National Union of Teachers
(KNUT) warned of a long teachers strike if the government rejects
any dialog with the teachers.
</P>
<P>
"There is no solution in sight. And we are not breaking the
strike. The strike is effective and it will continue," KNUT
Secretary-General Ambrose Adongo said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government signed the pay rise agreement last
December just before the second multi-party general elections
held at the end of that month.
</P>
<P>
Teachers' salaries range from 2,700 Shillings to 29,000
Shillings (45 to 480 U.S. Dollars) a month, relatively higher
than most other civil servants in the east African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
