<HEADLINE> MSF-Spain Ordered to Stop Medical Work in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Faction leader Ali Mahdi
Mohamed has informed the international aid agency of MSF-Spain it
cannot be trusted for the treatment of cholera in the Somali
capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
In a letter recently sent to the offices of the European Union
and the Somali Health Sector Coordination Body (SHSCB) in
Nairobi, Ali Mahdi said MSF-Spain is not professionally and
ethically committed to the Treatment Centers of Cholera in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The letter has also been sent to the offices of MSF-Spain,
World Health Organization, the United Nations Children's Fund and
the governor of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Ali Mahdi accused MSF-Spain of unexpectedly
abandoning its cholera activities in Mogadishu at a time when
hundreds of cholera victims were in the quarantine centers who
died in their dozens due to supply shortages following the
MSF-Spain's evacuation this April.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi has informed the agency that for this he will not
trust the MSF-Spain for the management of the cholera treatment
centers of Mogadishu this year and therefore urged the other
international NGOs to step in to take its place while vowing to
provide maximum collaboration for them.
</P>
<P>
Since the epidemic disease of cholera breaks out in Somalia
every last quarter of the year, the aid agency of MSF-Spain was
all the time in the past entrusted to handle the management of
cholera cases.
</P>
<P>
It is not known what has brought about these crises between
Ali Mahdi's faction and the local health authority on one side
and the MSF-Spain on the other. However, people know that
MSF-Spain has pull its expatriates out of Mogadishu along with
the other aid agencies following the nine-day-long abduction of
the 10 Red Cross staff members in April.
</P>
<P>
This letter came also at a time when new preparations are
being taken against the possible outbreak of cholera. 
</P>
</TEXT>
