<HEADLINE> Ghana, Nigeria Pledge Good Governance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and Nigeria reaffirmed
Saturday their commitment to good governance as the basis for
harmonious development and internal peace.
</P>
<P>
The commitment was made in a communique issued at the end of a
two-day visit to Ghana by General Abdulsalam Abubakar, Nigerian
Head of State, a special story by Ghana News Agency (GNA)
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two leaders reaffirmed their
determination to strive for preservation of peace and stability
for the socio-economic development of the west Africa sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry John Rawlings and the visiting
Nigerian leader reiterated the importance of the West Africa Gas
Pipeline project to the economic development and integration of
the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
They expressed satisfaction at the progress made so far and
urged that further concrete measures should be taken to ensure
its early realization.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two heads of state expressed concern
about the difficult economic situation in Africa and called for
renewed impetus toward regional groupings on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"African countries should harness their efforts with a view to
accelerating the economic integration process in the face of the
challenges of globalization," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings and Abubakar reiterated the adherence of their
respective countries to the principles and objectives of the
United Nations and the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
President Rawlings commended General Abubakar for his bold
initiatives and commitment to the program of transition to
democracy in Nigeria since he took over power about four months
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
