<HEADLINE> Lesotho King Asks Supporters to Leave Royal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho King Letsie III
Saturday appealed to opposition party supporters gathered at the
grounds of the royal palace in Maseru, capital of Lesotho, to
disperse and go home peacefully.
</P>
<P>
In a public address delivered on state radio monitored here,
the king stressed the need for Lesotho's politicians to put aside
their differences and to place the interests of the country and
its people above all.
</P>
<P>
The opposition supporters have been camping at the royal
palace since early August as part of a determined protest against
the country's May 23 general election, which, they claimed, was
rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
Letsie appealed to political leaders to ask their supporters
to refrain from protest action that would heighten the already
volatile situation in Lesotho, saying: "they should stop making
any provocative statements."
</P>
<P>
"I want to repeat that the best way of resolving problems is
through negotiations," he said, noting the last two sets of
face-to-face talks between the country's rival parties were a
positive sign.
</P>
<P>
The king said he was hopeful that the next round of these
talks, scheduled for Wednesday, would enhance efforts to bring
peace and stability to the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Letsie also extended his condolences to the families of
Lesotho and South African soldiers and civilians killed during
skirmishes which followed a Southern African Development
Community (SADC) intervention in late September.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen Lesotho soldiers and eight South African army men
died in gun battles when the SADC force intervened in Lesotho in
an effort to prevent what was termed a coup in the making.
</P>
</TEXT>
