<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece Anxious Over Israeli-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Greece expressed
their anxiety over military cooperation between Israel and Turkey
on Saturday, despite Israel's promise that such ties harm no one.
</P>
<P>
The anxiety was first expressed by Cypriot Speaker of the House
of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou in his opening address to a
one-day conference on "Greece-Cyprus-Israel: The New Challenges
for Regional Cooperation," organized by the Cyprus Research Center
(KYKEM) in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between Israel and Cyprus have improved to such a
great extent" that Israeli President Ezer Weizman will visit
Cyprus early next month while the Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Speaker Dan Tichon invited Kyprianou to pay a visit to Israel, the
house speaker said.
</P>
<P>
However, Kyprianou expressed the "anxiety of the people of
Cyprus" in relation to the military agreements between Israel and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Noting that he has had some explanation from the Israeli
government over the military agreements, he said, "to be honest, I
am not satisfied."
</P>
<P>
"One can not ignore the fact that Israel is providing Turkey
with high technology in the field of armaments," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Greek Ambassador to Cyprus Kyriakos Rodousakis
told delegates that while Greece did not doubt the assurances of
the Israeli government, "we do not rely on the good intention and
good will of Turkey."
</P>
<P>
He said the Israel-Turkey military agreement is encouraging
particularly the intransigence of Ankara toward Greece and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Ambassador to Cyprus Shemi Tzur, in his
speech, clarified that the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation
"is not a military alliance."
</P>
<P>
"It is not an agreement aimed at harming either Cyprus, or
Greece or any other third party," Tzur said, adding "Israel wants
to see a solution to the Cyprus problem. Israel always supported
more international effort to enhance stability in the Eastern
Mediterranean and will not take any measures to jeopardize that
effort."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Israeli ambassador said his country believes
that peace and stability among Cyprus, Greece and Turkey will
contribute to a comprehensive peace in the Eastern Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have enjoyed close military ties since 1996
when they signed two military cooperation agreements. But they
have triggered strong criticism from Turkey's neighbors,
particularly Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
According to KYKEM President Tonis Toumazis, the conference
will discuss the issues like "evaluation of important structural
changes in the Eastern Mediterranean and the Near East in the
Post-Cold War era," "ongoing regional developments" and "the
developing of political and military dynamics in the Eastern
Mediterranean." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
