<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Accuses Burundi of Backing Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kinshasa Saturday accused
Burundi of joining Rwanda and Uganda in supporting rebels
fighting to oust President Laurent Kabila, a report reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, Uganda and Burundi were helping ethnic Tutsis
spearheading the rebellion to set up a Tutsi homeland in east
Congo (K), Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo was quoted as telling
a news conference in the Congo capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fact. The Burundians are completely involved," Mwenze
said, adding that Kinshasa had reports of many trucks crossing
the border from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"The reports concerning the mass movement also mention the
constitution of an autonomous Banyamulenge (Congolese Tutsi) army
there which is receiving weapons from Burundi, Rwanda and Uganda
to protect the territory they are setting up," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the reports indicated trucks owned by the
U.N. and other international non-governmental agencies were also
being used to ferry Burundian Tutsis into the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DPC).
</P>
<P>
The Nucleus of the planned Tutsi homeland was in Uvira, a
bastion of Banyamulenge Tutsis who spearheaded the rebellion in
Kabila's army that has spread to become a widening regional
conflict, Mwenze charged.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Tutsis were being brought to Uvira from the
Congolese towns of Moba, Kalemie and Fizi and from Burundi and
Rwanda, describing any planned Tutsisland as "a permanent danger"
and a potential launchpad for attacks on Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Chad intervene in Congo on
behalf of Kabila while Sudan denied having troops in Congo.
</P>
<P>
Uganda admitted having soldiers in Congo to fight its own
rebels while Rwanda denied direct involvement. It is the first
time Congo accused Burundi of involving in the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Tutsi-led rebels launched a revolt on August 2 in the east
after Kabila kicked out Rwandan troops who had helped him topple
late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Rebels hold most major towns in the east, especially those
bordering Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi, and Congo's third city of
Kisangani in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
Clashes have been reported in the past few days in Kindu, a
government major forward base in the east, and Kinshasa said
Friday the loyalists had the upper hand on the battlefield and
that the rebels had been pushed back to Kalima, about 80 km
northeast of Kindu.
</P>
<P>
Mwenze said army chiefs were drawing up plans for a promised
government counter-offensive to take back rebel-held towns in the
east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
