<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Doubts Israel's Willingness for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 10 (Xinhua) -- One day after the Israeli hero
in a number of wars with Arabs Ariel Sharon was appointed as
foreign minister, Lebanon Saturday expressed shock and suspicion
about the Jewish state's willingness to achieve peace in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Naming Sharon as foreign minister makes Lebanon and other
Arab countries to ask if Israel wants to make peace or not,"
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri said in an interview with
Lebanon's Orient radio.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old Sharon was Israeli defense minister during the
Israeli second invasion of Lebanon in 1982.
</P>
<P>
He was forced to quit a year later after an Israeli inquiry
found him responsible for the massacre of hundreds of Palestinian
refugees in Beirut's Sabra and Chatila camps by Israeli-allied
Christian Lebanese militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that the appointment of Sharon reflected the
Israeli government's determination to continue its intransigence
during the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim to protect its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
But heavy casualties of Israeli troops in the border enclave
have forced Israel into considering withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Israel offered to pull out its troops
from south Lebanon in return for Lebanese government's security
guarantees for its north.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the proposal, asking Israel to fully comply
with the United Nations Resolution 425 which calls on Israel to
withdraw from Lebanon without any conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
