<HEADLINE> Taliban Representative to Have Talks With UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A representative of the
Afghan Taliban militia arrived here Saturday night for talks with
visiting the U.N. Secretary General's Special Envoy Lakhdar
Brahimi.
</P>
<P>
Maulvi Wakil Ahmed Mutawakil, the senior advisor to Taliban
supreme leader Mulla Omar, met Pakistani officials and discussed
with them matters relating to the mission of the special envoy
shortly after his arrival, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Maulvi Mutawakil will renew Mulla
Omar's invitation to Brahimi to visit the war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived here Thursday night from Tehran, accompanied by
the representative of the Organization of the Islamic Conference,
Ibrahim Bakar, on the second leg of their mission to reduce
tension between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here, Brahimi told the press that he had
received Mulla Omar's invitation but he could not go to
Afghanistan because of security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The sources disclosed that Maulvi Mutawakil said on Friday the
Taliban had extended an invitation to Brahimi to visit Afghanistan
for talks with Taliban leaders inside the country instead of
Islamabad and were waiting for his response.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the U.N. envoy's mission to visit Afghanistan and
hold talks with Taliban leaders on Iran-Taliban tension, Maulvi
Mutawakil said.
</P>
<P>
He added: "It is not the first occasion that Brahimi is
visiting the region. He had visited Afghanistan in the past and we
hope that he will positively respond to our invitation."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. had withdrawn its staff from Kabul a few days before
the U.S. missile strike on alleged bases of Osama Bin Laden in
Khost. One U.N. official was killed in Kabul during the anti-U.S.
demonstration following the strike in August. 
</P>
