<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Portugal Seal Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano announced Saturday that his government has signed three
agreements here with Portugal.
</P>
<P>
One accord is on debt service postponement of 83.1 million
U.S. Dollars, which is equal to Mozambique's total debt and
interest to Portugal from July 1, 1997 to June 30, 1999, Chissano
made the announcement at a joint press conference here with
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres.
</P>
<P>
However, the president did not reveal the terms and deadline
of the postponement.
</P>
<P>
Under the second pact, Portugal is to donate 2.53 million
Dollars to Mozambique to help restore the Cuamba-Entrelagos
railway.
</P>
<P>
The 77-km-long railway is in Niassa Province in northern
Mozambique, which is part of the Nacala Development Corridor.
</P>
<P>
The third is a protocol for technical cooperation. Under this
agreement, Portugal will offer Mozambique technical counseling
and vocational training in the financial sector and the customs.
</P>
<P>
Chissano believed that Guterres' visit to Mozambique which
started on October 6 has consolidated the friendly cooperative
relations between the two countries and peoples.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese prime minister concluded his five-day official
visit Saturday with commitment to keeping his country's promise
in relieving Mozambique's debt burden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
