<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for Early End to Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan, the
Regent made a call on Saturday for an early lifting of the
eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He made the call at a meeting with Iraqi First Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz which focused on Aziz's recent meetings with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and other U.N. officials in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Aziz arrived here earlier Saturday on a brief stop after
concluding a 10-day visit to the U.N., where he discussed with
U.N. officials on resuming cooperation with the world body on
inspecting Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
On August 5 this year, Iraq ended its cooperation with the
U.N. weapons inspection team, alleging that team chief Richard
Butler refused to certify that Iraq had destroyed its banned
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Only after the U.N. makes sure that Iraq destroys all its
banned weapons, can the world body lift its sanctions which was
imposed on the country for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Hassan praised Aziz's efforts to settle Iraq's problems with
the world body, Jordan's official news agency, the Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
After his visit to the U.N., Aziz told the press on Friday in
Paris that Iraq still wants to pursue dialog with the U.N. to
resolve the weapons inspection crisis, although he failed to reach
an agreement with Annan on resuming searches of suspected weapon
sites in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan keeps a close eye on the development of the relations
between Iraq and the U.N., because Iraq is the kingdom's sole oil
provider and largest trade partner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
