<HEADLINE> Congolese Airliner Downed by Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A Congolese airliner was shot
down by rebels in the east of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) Saturday as it headed for Kinshasa, the capital city in the
southwest of the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted Congolese Information Minister Didier Mumengi
as saying the plane was brought down when it took off from Kindu,
where government army and rebels fighting to oust President
Laurent Kabila have been contending for its control.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said the Congolese Airlines (CAL) Boeing
727 was brought down after taking off from Kindu airport, whereas
rebels said they hit the plane as it was coming in to land at
Kindu, according to the Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
There are also conflicting sayings as to how many people were
aboard the plane and their identities.
</P>
<P>
A CAL director said the plane had 38 passengers, who were
mainly women and children, and three crew aboard, and that
rescuers are still checking for survivors.
</P>
<P>
But rebels claimed that more than 40 government soldiers had
been killed in the incident.
</P>
<P>
"Once again the aggressors have attacked a civilian target,"
said Mumengi, who added that this did not mean rebels had taken
control of the airport.
</P>
<P>
So far, no details were given by the government as for when
the plane was hit, neither were the exact casualti.
</P>
<P>
After winning battles on the west of Congo (K) with the aid of
troops from Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia, Kabila's army and its
alliance are now fighting in the east which is the rebels'
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Kabila now accuses Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi of backing the
Tutsi rebels to fight against his 16-month-old administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
