<HEADLINE> Presidential Elections in Azerbaijan Declared Valid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The presidential elections held
in Azerbaijan on Sunday have been declared valid, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
A total of 31.9 percent of voters had cast ballot papers. Under
the law on presidential elections in the country, elections are
considered valid when the rate of ballot is more than 25 percent
of all eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
A source from Azerbaijan's Central Election Commission said
that the situation is tranquil and no serious violations in the
voting regulations have been revealed.
</P>
<P>
The presidential candidates include 75-year-old current
president Heydar Aliyev, chairman of the Social Well-Being Party
Khangusein Kyazimli, chairman of one of the three Azerbaijani
Communist parties Firudin Gasanov, president of the Political
Repression Victims' Association Ashraf Mekhtiyev, Chairman of the
National Independence Party Etibar Mamedov and Independent
Azerbaijan Party leader Nizami Suleymanov.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the election law, a candidate gathers more
than 33 percent of votes in favor of the ballots, he will win the
elections. If nobody won the percent of affirmative votes in the
first round of elections, then the first two candidates, who get
the most votes in favor in the first round, will hold the second
round of elections, where the candidate, who wins the more
affirmative votes, will be the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
