<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Azerbaijan's Presidential Elections Declared Valid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The presidential elections held
in Azerbaijan on Sunday have been declared valid, according to the
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Although only 31.9 percent of voters cast ballots, the
elections are considered valid. Under the country's law on
presidential elections, voting is valid if the voter turn-out rate
exceeds 25 percent of all eligible voters.
</P>
<P>
The situation was calm and no serious violations of the voting
regulations have been reported, according to a source in
Azerbaijan's Central Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidates include 75-year-old current President
Heydar Aliyev, Social Well-Being Party Chairman Khangusein
Kyazimli, chairman of one of the three Azerbaijani Communist
parties Firudin Gasanov, president of the Political Repression
Victims' Association Ashraf Mekhtiyev, chairman of the National
Independence Party Etibar Mamedov, and Independent Azerbaijan
Party leader Nizami Suleymanov.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, a candidate who gathers more than 33
percent of votes in favor will be winner of the elections. If
nobody wins the required percentage of affirmative votes in the
first round of elections, the two candidates who get the most
affirmative votes will contest in a second round and the winner
will be the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
