<HEADLINE> EDS: Updated With More Details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- All six U.S. B-52 bombers
touched down in Britain Sunday afternoon in preparation for
possible NATO air strikes against Yugoslav military targets over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The six bombers landed at Fairford air base near London about
15 minutes apart, starting shortly before midday. The huge bombers
had left American Barksdale Air Force Base in Louisiana Saturday
evening to make the long flight.
</P>
<P>
Major Robyn Grantham of the U.S. Air Force told British Sky
Television that while the B-52s could carry a series of different
weapons, "they are looking more at the conventional air-launched
cruise missiles" in possible military action in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Defense Secretary George Robertson was
quoted by Sky Television as saying early Sunday the arrival of the
American bombers "is not a token gesture."
</P>
<P>
"There will be a phased series of air attacks on the Yugoslav
military force if he (Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic) does
not comply with the will of the world," Robertson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
