<HEADLINE> Camenzind Wins Swiss First Road Title in 47 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Oscar Camenzind brought home
the first world professional road race title in 47 years for
Switzerland when the cycling race ended in Valkenburg of the
Netherlands on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He finished alone and 23 seconds clear of Belgian Peter Van
Petegem, who beat Italian Michele Bartoli for the bronze in the
258-kilometer event after more than six hours racing in cold and
rain.
</P>
<P>
Ferdi Kuebler was the last Swiss professional to win a
professional world road race championship at the Italian town of
Varese in 1951.
</P>
<P>
The professional class was renamed elite two years ago when
Camenzind's team mate Mauro Gianetti was beaten for the gold by
Belgian Johan Museeuw in Lugano.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday Camenzind upset the odds when in the last 11 k
ilometers he escaped from his five co-leaders, who included
pre-race favorites Bartoli, Dutchman Michael Boogerd and American
Lance Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
Armstrong, who a year ago was battling cancer, finished
fourth, one minute and nine seconds behind Camenzind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
