<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Interviewed on His Visit to Uzbekistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said on Sunday that Uzbekistan plays an important role in the
Central Asian region, and the relationship with Uzbekistan is one
of the directions of priority importance in the politics in the
CIS space.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told journalists of the Itar-Tass, Zhakhon (Uzbekistan)
and Khabar (Kazakhstan) news agencies before departure to Tashkent
that he attaches great significance to his state visit to
Uzbekistan where he is to sign a package of documents on bilateral
cooperation, including an Agreement and a program of deepening
economic integration between the two counties for a term of ten
years.
</P>
<P>
"We have mutually defined these relations as the relations of
strategic partnership and comprehensive cooperation. These
relations are based not only on long-standing traditions of
friendship, mutual respect and sincere mutual sympathy between the
people of the two countries and close contacts in the economic
field, but on the common vision of many processes under way in the
region and in the world," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the cooperation between Russia and Uzbekistan has
been deepening and becoming more dynamic, recalling the talks with
Uzbek President Islam Karimov in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Yeltsin also admitted that the activities for
the development of interaction in the humanitarian field fall far
short of the specified goals.
</P>
<P>
There are financial and economic difficulties, the Russian
president said, adding that another thing hindering bilateral
relations was slowness and lack of vigor.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Yeltsin said, he intends to discuss with
leaders of Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan the situation in Afghanistan
and on the CIS southern borders and he reaffirmed that "Moscow comes
out for political settlement of this problem under the UN
auspices."
</P>
<P>
They will discuss concrete steps taken to neutralize a threat
posed by Afghanistan to the security and stability in the region,
Yeltsin continued.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that "we are for the political settlement of
the Afghan problem under the UN auspices."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin left Moscow for Uzbekistan on a state visit on Sunday
morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
