<HEADLINE> Reactivation of Used Catalysts Viable: Researcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti researcher said
the optimum way to treat used catalysts is their reactivation,
which not only is environment-friendly, but also saves a lot of
money.
</P>
<P>
Mina Maarafi, director of the oil refining program under the
Kuwait Institute for Scientific Research, said that after nearly
10 years of studies, a new method has been found that can make the
used catalysts regain over 90 percent of original characteristics.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency reported (Kuna) Sunday, Mina said the eff
icient method could be used for the catalysts
employed in the hydrogenation of heavy oil by Kuwaiti refineries.
</P>
<P>
The new method resembles removal of oil precipitation by
testing the consumed catalysts and knowing their physical,
chemical and mechanical characteristics, she said. But she did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The used catalysts, which are toxic, were kept in special
depots, but this endangers the environment by time because of the
leakage of toxic components to the soil and groundwater.
</P>
<P>
Another method is the extraction of heavy metals from the used
catalysts, she said, but this is no more viable because of the
fall of prices of heavy metals.
</P>
<P>
Mina concluded that the reactivation of lightly polluted
catalysts was the optimum economic investment. This project will
succeed both technically and economically and will put an end to
some current environment problems, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
