<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish, Yugoslav PMs to Discuss Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANTALYA (TURKEY), October 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz and his Yugoslav counterpart Momir Bulatovic will
meet later this afternoon to discuss the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be one of the several important bilateral
contacts before a Balkan summit that is to start in southern
Turkish port city of Antalya Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Yilmaz-Bulatovic meeting is expected to focus on the
Kosovo crisis, which has become more tense following a NATO's
warning of a military strike to force Belgrade to withdraw its
forces from the war-stricken region.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds have died and thousands others been displaced since
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic launched a crackdown on
February 28 against the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army,
which is fighting to wrest Kosovo province from Serbia, the main
republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million inhabitants are ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Bulatovic will brief Yilmaz on the latest
developments of the Kosovo crisis and the Yugoslav government's
position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Turkish Parliament authorized cabinet to send
troops on a possible NATO peacekeeping mission aimed at stopping
the bloody conflicts in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has close ties with ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, has repeatedly urged the Yugoslav government to take
concrete and effective measures to stop the violence there.
</P>
<P>
Ankara decided last August that Turkey will provide four F-16
fighters if NATO launches air strikes against Yugoslavia's
military targets in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will also meet his Yugoslav
counterpart Zivadin Jovanovic later.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav delegation arrived here this afternoon for the
Balkan summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
