<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Helps American Find Former China Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Septuagenarian Joseph Ferm and
his wife left Beijing today bound for his childhood home in
Longshan Village in the city of Zhangqiu, east China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Olof and Pauline Ferm, his parents, worked and stayed in the
small village between 1928-1936. His father, a Swedish citizen,
opened a village school and his mother, an American, ran a small
clinic. Ferm's two younger brothers and a sister were born in the
village.
</P>
<P>
Ferm and his mother returned to the United States in 1949 and
he himself later worked hard and became a senior engineer at a
California aircraft plant.
</P>
<P>
The elderly American had cherished the fond dream of visiting
his childhood home for decades, but failed to remember the
location of the small Chinese village. Earlier this year, however,
he began searching for information concerning "Lungshan" on the
Internet. He sent an E-Mail massage to the Chinese Business
(Huashang) World" and finally succeeded in his search with the
ensuing help of a Jinan newspaper named "Qilu (Shandong) Evening
News".
</P>
<P>
They arrived in Beijing last Friday to fulfill their
long-cherished dream. "It will be an exciting and unforgetable
journey," said Ferm.
</P>
<P>
Prior to leaving the United States, Ferm purchased a new pair
of glasses to make sure that he would be able to clearly see the
New China.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that small village sits near the Yellow River. "I
remember a nearby old temple housing a number of solemn
sculptures," said Ferm. "I'm going to look for the old gates and
walls, stroll along the sandy beach, sit quietly by the river, and
renew childhood friendships."
</P>
<P>
A host of childhood Chinese friends still remember Ferm. For
example, Zhang Yuheng, 76, recalled pulling the cart and playing
childhood games with Ferm, and Dou Shengwen, also 76, remembered
very clearly when the Ferm's lived in the village. "We had never
before seen car, motorcycle or bicycles like the Ferm's brought to
the village," said Dou.
</P>
<P>
A number of elderly villagers recalled the friendly foreign
family as good neighbors. They also recounted how Ferm's mother
graciously provided medicine to locals suffering from various
illnesses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
