<HEADLINE> U.S. B-52 Bombers Arrive in U.K. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Six American B-52 bombers are
arriving in Britain on Sunday in preparation for possible NATO air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The first two of the six bombers have landed at Fairford RAF
base in Gloucestershire, 120 km west of London, as U.K. Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook again warned Serbia it is running out of time
over Kosovo, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The remaining four are due within hours, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The B-52s can carry out bombing missions anywhere in the world
from bases in the United States, but moving six planes to the
U.K. shortens the range and is meant to increase pressure on
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The planes can carry up to 30 tons of bombs and missiles, but
satellite guided cruise missiles are likely to be used. The
U.S. has also sent 13 in-flight refueling tankers to the U.K,
according to BBC.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that every day of delay for Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic was a "lost opportunity," noting that "he is
certainly running out of time."
</P>
<P>
The U.K. foreign secretary said he was "confident" that NATO
would be united over action on Kosovo at its meeting on Monday.
</P>
