<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The week-long 16th congress
of the Communist Party of India (Marxist) (CPI(M)) ended in
Calcutta Sunday after adopting a political resolution and
organizational reports and electing a new 67-member central
committee.
</P>
<P>
CPI (M) General Secretary Harkishen Singh Surjeet was
unanimously re-elected at the newly formed central committee, the
party's highest policy-making body, according to press reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the concluding session, Surjeet reiterated his
call for making serious efforts to forge a third front in the
country to counter the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP).
</P>
<P>
"We have to rally all secular and democratic forces to achieve
our end," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to go to the people with the message that the
country's economic sovereignty is under severe threat and that
democracy is in danger at the hands of the communal forces in
power. Besides, mass movements would have to be launched against
price rises, in which our party will take a leading role," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for strengthening the party's mass
organizations in order to achieve the ideals of socialism, adding
that all shortcomings would be overcome by making sincere efforts
and strictly adhering to the communist ideology. 
</P>
