<HEADLINE> Philippine President Arrives in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada arrived in Singapore Sunday for a four-day state visit at
the invitation of Singapore President Ong Teng Cheong.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, accompanied by a 16-member team of government
officials as well as a 70-member business delegation, is making
his first foreign visit since he became president of the
Philippines 15 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with some 1,000 representatives from the Filipino
community in Singapore shortly after his arrival, Estrada said he
would continue to work in favor of the poor as president of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked Philippine overseas workers for their
contribution to the Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Estrada will meet with Singapore leaders for
talks on bilateral relations, regional problems and other matters
of mutual interest, and will attend a singing ceremony for six
business agreements with a total of 300 million U.S. dollars in
investment fund.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will also deliver a keynote speech at the October 12-14
Seventh East Asia Economic Summit organized by the
Switzerland-based World Economic Forum in partnership with the
Singapore Economic Development Board.
</P>
<P>
A Local Chinese newspaper, "Lianhe Zaobao," Sunday quoted
Philippine Foreign Minister Domingo Siazon as saying that Estrada
will travel next Tuesday to the Indonesian island of Batam, which
is close to Singapore, to meet with Indonesian President Habibie
for talks on bilateral economic cooperation, ASEAN affairs, the
forthcoming APEC summit to be held in Kuala Lumpur next month, as
well as the situation in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is the third largest trade partner of the
Philippines. Bilateral trade rose to 7.44 billion Singapore
dollars (4.65 billion U.S. dollars) last year, a 41.1 percent
increase over 1996. In the first seven months of this year, it
reached 4.56 billion Singapore dollars (2.85 billion U.S.
dollars), an increase of 15.8 percent over the same period last
year. 
</P>
