<HEADLINE> Djiboutian Pilot Detained in Somalia for Shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A Djiboutian pilot was
detained Saturday in the Somali northeastern port town of Bossaso
for his plane carrying Somali refugees from Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the local authority of Bossaso said that the
Djiboutian pilot has been detained, accused of bringing Somali
refugees without the consent of the northeastern regional
authorities, said a report reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The pilot has also been accused of bringing Somali refugees
from Yemen and dropping them in Bossaso without the approval of
the local authorities.
</P>
<P>
The Radio station in Galkaio Town, which supports the recently
announced disputed administration of Puntland, reported that the
pilot will be tried by the regional court later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Puntland authorities said that the pilot has earlier been
warned, but he evidently ignored the warning.
</P>
<P>
The detention of the Djiboutian pilot together with his plane
may not help the already strained relationship between Somalia's
northeastern authorities and the Republic of Djibouti led by
President Hassan Gouled Aptidon, following the abduction of a
commercial vessel from Djibouti by members from the Northeastern
militiamen late September.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen who still hold the vessel "Nur Star" are asking
for a huge ransom of 100,000 U.S. Dollars for the release of the
ship.
</P>
<P>
The elders from the area are working hard for the
unconditional release of the ship.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the repatriation of the Somali refugees from
abroad has especially been high in the northwestern regions of
Somalia now known as the break-away republic of Somaliland.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats from the Scandinavian countries have for several
times dropped Somali refugees from their countries to the
northwestern Somali towns of Hargeysa and Berbera without the
approval of Somaliland authorities in 1995 and 1996, in which the
pilots and planes were detained and fined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
