<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build First Ape-man Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China's leading
paleoanthropological research group plans to build its first
museum to display treasured ape-man and hominid fossils, as well
as other traces of communal culture excavated in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
Fong Yun-wah, a Hong Kong compatriot who is eager to promote
China's cultural eduction, today donated 1.3 million yuan (157,000
U.S. dollars) to the Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and
Paleoanthropology, a branch of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences(CAS), to fund the Shuhua Museum of Paleoanthropology.
</P>
<P>
"The paleoanthropological displays will represent scientific
achievements in the field," said CAS President Lu Yongxiang,
adding that "they will help popularize science and knowledge
amongst the general public."
</P>
<P>
The institute, the only research body of its kind in China, has
recorded monumental achievements in studying the earth's earliest
inhabitants and their use of tools. Research groups from the
institute have unearthed fossils of Peking Man, and Lantian
anthropoids and ape-men in Lufeng. The groups have also discovered
cultural ruins dating back to the Paleolithic Period in the upper
reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The institute operates museum's in the southwestern suburbs of
Beijing, the Chinese capital, featuring displays of remote ancient
animals and the fossils of Peking Man at the Zhoukoudian Ruins.
</P>
<P>
Fong's family foundation is fully supporting the ambitious
museum development plans formulated by Chinese
paleoanthropologists.
</P>
<P>
Fong, 74, previously donated over 150 million Hong Kong dollars
(19.3 million U.S. dollars) to establish over 40 schools across
the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
