<HEADLINE> Nigerians Held Hostage by Chadian Rebels: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Residents of at least nine
villages in border area of Borna State are now being held hostage
by the rebel groups from the Republic of Chad as a shield against
attacks by the joint force of Nigeria, Chad and Niger.
</P>
<P>
The three neighboring countries are carrying out a joint
military operation known as " Operation Flush Out" to launch air,
land and sea raids on suspected rebels from Chad, Nigerian
newspaper The Post Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report revealed a heavy presence of military personnel
drawn from the three countries and a massive presence of heavy
weapons including armored tanks and artillery guns.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the joint military force is seated in
Baga, northeast Nigeria, at Lake Chad.
</P>
<P>
The joint force has been engaged in searching of the rebels'
hideout and intensified attacks on some of rebel camps which
forced the rebels to capture villagers in the area.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar Sadiq, a villager who escaped from the rebels, was
quoted as saying that the well-armed rebels numbering about 3,000
are holding the Nigerian villagers as a shield against attacks by
the joint force on their camps.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held last August in Nigerian capital Abuja to
discuss security problems on their common border, Nigeria, Chad
and Niger decided to set up a joint committee to combat criminal
activities in Lake Chad area.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, a joint military force was deployed along
the common border areas of the three countries as the rebels from
Chad have posed a serious threat to peace, security and stability
in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
