<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Boost Dairy Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia is kicking off a
program to revive and boost the country's dairy industry, in a
hope to address domestic needs and increase export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "White Revolution," the nine-year national program
effective from this year apparently borrows some of the idea of
India's successful "Green Revolution" starting in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
However, as a top official of the Mongolian Dairy Farmers
Association told the press here in a recent interview, the program
is tailored to tap this inland nation's vast grassland resources.
</P>
<P>
At a price tag of 110 billion togrog (about 129.4 million
U.S. dollars), it will initially involve three to five counties in
each of the 11 participating provinces and then spread nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Together with cash injection from foreign aid resources, and
domestic private and corporate investors, state funding would help
import equipment and technologies for making dairy products.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that Mongolia has witnessed successive livestock
harvests in recent years, providing enough raw materials for the
industry, a total of 450 diary factories are planned nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
