<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sihanouk Says He Could Not Preside Over Summit Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King Norodom
Sihanouk said on Sunday that he could not preside over a
three-party summit now because the opposition has yet to formally
put forward their request for such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The king made the remarks in response to Chea Sim, president of
the ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP), who sent a letter to
Sihanouk Saturday asking him to preside over a summit to help
break the political impasse and hammer out a deal to form a
government.
</P>
<P>
"I could not preside over a summit meeting now because I could
not ask Prince Ranariddh, President of FUNCINPEC, and Sam Rainsy,
President of his self-named party to come back from abroad to
participate (in) the summit, and it appears they also did not want
to return now," the king responded.
</P>
<P>
"The summit could not be held until they all agreed to and
asked me to do so," Sihanouk added.
</P>
<P>
The third round of coalition negotiations between the country's
three political parties collapsed Friday after the politicians
failed to agree on what to do about a controversial seat
allocation formula.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the multi-party negotiations, however, agreed
to ask King Sihanouk to preside over a summit aimed at breaking
the current political deadlock and forming a new government as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC leader prince Norodom Ranariddh is still in Bangkok
since he left Siem Reap on September 25, the day after the opening
of the National Assembly. Sam Rainsy, who left the country on the
same day, is on a tour of the United States and Europe to lobby
for support for the opposition. He is expected to come to Bangkok
on October 15.
</P>
<P>
Only 25 of the 43 FUNCINPEC Parliamentarians are now in
Cambodia and all the 15 Assembly members from the Sam Rainsy Party
are out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
