<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Lifts Sanctions on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group (CMAG) Saturday announced the lifting of sanctions
imposed on Nigeria in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the CMAG decided that Nigeria will not be re-admitted
into the Commonwealth until the inauguaration of an elected
civilian president on May 29, 1999, as it was provided by the
current democratization program.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG, comprising foreign ministers of Britain, Canada,
Ghana, jamaica, Malaysia, New Zealand, South Africa and Zimbabwe,
made the decision at its two-day meeting ending Friday in London.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Ignatius Olisemeka attended the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth in November 1995
after it hanged author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight minority activists
on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth also imposed various sanctions on Nigeria,
including suspending all forms of military co-operation,
restriction of development assistance, banning of sports exchange
and visa restrictions on government officials.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG was established then to monitor Nigeria's human
rights records to decide on further actions, including the total
expulsion of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports reaching here Sunday, Nigerian
foreign minister Olisemeka, while welcoming the CMAG decisions,
expressed reservations about linking's Nigeria's re-admission to
the return of democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
The international community is right to adopt a wait-and-see
attitude towards Nigeria on the issue of re-admission, he said.
But the Nigerian military government led by General Abdulsalami
Abubakar is determined to hand over to a civilian government next
year, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
