<HEADLINE> Italian Management, Labor Urge Budget Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Italy's business and union leaders
urged Saturday the parliament to pass the cabinet's budget
proposal and avoid the risk of a temporary government shut-down.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here, CGIL Secretary General Sergio Cofferati said
the budget must be passed because temporary shut-down would hurt
the nation in terms of stability and its future capabilities.
</P>
<P>
"In any case," said Giorgio Fossa, president of Confindustria,
is "a dangerous thing when it coincides with the current
international crisis, with a recession on the doorstep."
</P>
<P>
"The budget itself is not that great," Fossa said in his
capacity as head of Italy's industrial employers association, "it
is a normal measure in an extraordinary situation."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some leaders also called for a quick solution to the
current government crisis stemmed from the resignation Friday of
former Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the interest of the nation that there is an efficient
government as quickly as possible," BNI Chairman Luigi Abete said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi stepped down after losing the vote of confidence at the
lower house of parliament, but has been asked by President Oscar
Scalfaro to head a caretaker government pending his replacement.
</P>
</TEXT>
