<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels in Congo (k) Down Airliner With Over 40 on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 11 (Xinhua)-- Rescuers Sunday are searching
through dense jungle for survivors on a Congolese airliner shot
down by rebels with over 40 passengers and crew on board.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 727 belonging to the private Congolese Airlines (CAL)
was brought down Saturday around Kindu, a stronghold town of
forces backing President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC), said a report reaching here Sunday from Kinshasa,
capital of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the rebels and government officials
differed on who was on board -- mainly civilians or mainly
soldiers -- and the stage of the plane's flight when it was hit,
apparently by a missile.
</P>
<P>
The rebels warned that they would shoot down any aircraft
trying to land at Kindu Airport.
</P>
<P>
"All planes arriving in Kindu face a major risk of being shot
down," Alexis Tambwe, a senior rebel official, told a late night
news conference in the eastern rebel bastion of Goma.
</P>
<P>
Government and airline officials said the aircraft was brought
down after it took off from Kindu Airport bound for Kinshasa,
while rebels said they hit the plane as it was coming in to land
at Kindu.
</P>
<P>
A CAL director said the plane had 38 passengers and three crew
aboard.
</P>
<P>
the attack marked a sharp escalation in the two-month-old
civil war that has grown into a wider regional conflict
attracting some half a dozen African armies, diplomats in
Kinshasa said.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Didier Mumengi said the plane was hit as
it took off from Kindu, where loyalist troops and rebels opposed
to Kabila have been fighting for control of Kindu for days.
</P>
<P>
"Once again the aggressors have attacked a civilian target,"
added Mumengi. He said, however, that the attack did not mean
that rebels had control of the airport.
</P>
<P>
Kindu is surrounded by tropical rain forest rich in tin
deposits and is some 440 km (275 miles) southwest of Goma.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the CAL Director, Savros Papaioannou, as
saying that the plane apparently was struck by a missile. "We
have no idea of casualties, but a search is in progress for
survivors, if there are any," he said.
</P>
<P>
Airline sources said private airlines, including several
foreign charter outfits, have been playing an important role in
transporting troops and materials for Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Both CAL and the Congolese state carrier LAC have leased
planes in their fleet that are used to ferry troops and war
materials, said the report quoting airline sources.
</P>
<P>
Two leased Boeing 707 cargo planes -- one each for CAL and LAC
-- were seized on the tarmac in Goma at the start of the
rebellion on August 2 and used to transport rebel fighters to the
west of the country.
</P>
<P>
fighting between the ethnic Tutsi rebels and Kabila's forces
is now centred mainly on Kindu.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi of invading to
support Congolese Tutsis with origins in Rwanda. Kabila's forces
are being helped by troops from some African countries including
Angola, Zimbabwe and Chad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
