<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Meets Congo (K) Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa held talks here Saturday with Leader of the
Congolese rebel movement, Earnest Wamba dia Wamba, on the crisis
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The details of their talks were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was a fulfillment of a decision made at the
Mauritius summit of the 14-nation Southern African Development
Community (SADC) in September, local media reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a State House statement as saying that the
delegation of the Congolese Democratic Coalition headed by Wamba
also comprised head of the external relations department, Bizima
Karaha, and other two members, Michael Tshibwabwa and Etienne
Rusamira.
</P>
<P>
At the Mauritius summit, the presidents of Tanzania and Zambia
were charged with the task of contacting the parties who were not
heard at the conference but critical to a solution to the crisis
in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
In discharging the mission, the two presidents met Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni at Entebbe in southern Uganda on
September 19, and Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu and
Vice-President Paul Kagame the following day in Kigali, the
capital of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa has informed Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba of his meeting with Wamba and stressed the need for
stepped-up efforts to promote a negotiated settlement of the
Congo crisis, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, Leader of the Congolese Democratic Coalition, used to
work for the University of Dar es Salaam as a history professor
until he joined the ranks of the rebels against the government of
DRC President Laurent Kabila in early August this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
