<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan, U.N.-OIC Team Open Talks in Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban opened
talks here Sunday with the visiting envoys of the U.N. and the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) on the present
Iran-Afghan tension.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held their first session Sunday morning and the
Taliban team delivered a special message to U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi from Taliban leader Mohammad Omar,
inviting him to visit Afghanistan for detailed talks, official
sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Wakeel Ahmed Mutawakil, senior advisor to Mohammad Omar, who
flew into Islamabad Saturday night, delivered Omar's message,
Taliban's chief representative Saeedur Rehman Haqqani told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Haqqani said the Taliban will hold the second round of talks
with brahimi Sunday afternoon and will wait till evening for
Brahimi's response to Omar's message.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi and Ibrahim Baker, assistant General Secretary of OIC,
arrived here on Thursday on the second leg of their mission to
reduce tension between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and the Taliban failed till Friday to finalize the
venue for their meeting as Brahimi wanted the Taliban leaders to
come to Islamabad while the Taliban invited the U.N. envoy to
visit Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A special Pakistani plane brought Mutawakil to Islamabad
Saturday night. He met Pakistani officials in the Foreign Ministry
soon after his arrival and discussed with them matters relating to
the U.N.-OIC mission.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan played a key role to persuade the Taliban leadership
to come to Islamabad to save the U.N.-OIC peace mission from
failure.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi and Baker opened talks Friday with Pakistani officials
and discussed various options to peacefully resolve the dispute
between Iran and the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi's current visit to the region is in the context of
implementing the "Points of Common Understanding" that was reached
during the "Six Plus Two" Foreign Ministers' meeting in New York
on September 21.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Afghanistan's immediate neighbors plus
the U.S. and Russia evolved "Points of Common Understanding"
which include the cessation of hostilities in Afghanistan and a
number of confidence-building measures to promote the restoration
of durable peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
