<HEADLINE> Italian President to Talk Less Over Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Scalfaro
said Saturday that he would talk less over the issue of government
crisis to make a proper climate for its end.
</P>
<P>
As the crisis occurred in the government, Scalfaro said in
Florence, "parliament also enters this difficult phase and the
president finds himself in a very delicate position."
</P>
<P>
"There is no law which prohibits the head of state from
speaking," he said, but adding that he has the duty to reduce his
presence as much as possible and his words even less.
</P>
<P>
In speaking to the 20th congress of the National Veterans
Association in Florence, Scalfaro also said he would do less
official business as president and do more to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing government crisis occurred as former Prime Minister
Romano Prodi resigned Friday after he lost the vote of confidence
in the lower house of parliament by 312 to 313.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro has asked Prodi to head a caretaker government pending
his replacement. 
</P>
