<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelterbelt Project Proves Beneficial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The national campaign to
establish shelterbelts in north, northwest and northeast China
over the past two decades have proved highly beneficial.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the massive effort beginning in 1978, reportedly
the world's largest project of its kind, is to plant trees on 35.6
million ha over the next 53 years. The project will be carried out
with a cost of 57.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China's Jilin Province has planted shelterbelts
covering 865,000 ha, or 72 percent of total forests in the
region. Jilin's forest coverage rate has grown to 14.5 percent in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The province enjoys a vastly improved ecological environment,
with the volume of land subject to sandstorms falling from 7.3
million ha to only 310,000 ha. The province's annual grain output
stands at around 20 billion kilograms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
