<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Form Expert Panel to Probe Causes of Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Ministry of
Fisheries and Livestock will soon set up a special committee to
inquire into the causes of the recent death of fishes in the Bay
of Bengal, The Independent daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to comprise representatives of the
Department of Fisheries (DF), the Marine Fishery Resources Survey
Unit, the Marine Fisheries Research Institute (MFRI) and the
Institute of Marine Biology of the Chittagong University, the
report quoted a high-placed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fishes in the Bay of Bengal were behaving strangely for the
past four months and of late a large number of dead fishes was
found floating in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the DF and MFRI had collected samples of the dead
fishes from the Cox's Bazar area, 314 kilometers southeast of
Dhaka, during the last few days.
</P>
<P>
Initial findings show that the 90 percent of the dead fishes
were small species of marine "poa", a bottom feeder, and "latya",
another bottom feeder, was also found dead in the Bay, he added.
</P>
<P>
Experts dissected the belly of the dead fishes but hardly found
anything that would conclusively prove the cause of their death,
he stated.
</P>
<P>
A Chittagong-based researcher has proposed sending the samples
of dead fish to Thailand for bacteriological tests.
</P>
<P>
Senior DF officials, however, are skeptical about the outcome
of such tests, saying that after death the floating fishes might
be under secondary bacterial attack and thus bacterial tests on
dead fishes might give misleading results.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that death of fishes might have been caused
by physio-chemical factors which should be identified. Excessive
growth of Red-Tid, one specie of plankton that creates shortage of
dissolved oxygen in sea water, might also be a contributing
factor, they added.
</P>
<P>
Some officials feel that the dissolved oxygen content of the
Bay waters might be reduced also by the flushing of huge volume of
flood waters that are washing out agro-chemical residue, and other
toxic wastes from the catchment areas in both India and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
They are optimistic about the capability of the Institute of
Marine Biology of the Chittagong University to identify the cause
of death of fishes in the Bay.
</P>
<P>
However, either the DF, nor MFRI or the Institute of Marine
Biology has the necessary expertise to test the heavy metal
toxicity that might also be a cause of fish death due to dumping
of toxic wastes by foreign ships, fisheries officials said.
</P>
<P>
Marine fishes account for over 21 percent of the nearly 1.4
million tons of fishes consumed annually in this South Asian
country, according to official figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
