<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Lebanese Guerrillas Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Two fighters of Lebanon's
resistance forces were killed late Saturday night in clashes with
Israeli occupation troops in south Lebanon, security sources said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas of the Hezbollah, or Party of God, were killed
when they were attempting to attack an Israeli post at the village
of Rihan in the east of Israel's self-styled security zone, the
sources added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army has confirmed the casualties, Lebanon's Orient
radio reported. Hezbollah still remained silent.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to
protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by Lebanese
guerrillas. The Jewish state is mired in a war of attrition.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is spearheading a resistance movement aimed at
driving more than 1,000 Israeli troops out of the country. 
</P>
