<HEADLINE>   Peace Guarantors to Propose Ecuador-Peru Border Formula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Argentina, Brazil, Chile and the
United States, the guarantor countries for talks on the border
dispute between Ecuador and Peru, on Saturday agreed to work out a
proposal for a border delimitation formula between the two
countries, said the Ecuadoran Foreign Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The move is in response to a request made this week by
Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad and his Peruvian counterpart
Albert Fujimori for a formula by guarantors to determine the
border line between the two countries in unmarked zones.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Mahuad and Fujimori, Brazilian President
Fernando Cardoso, in capacity of coordinator of the guarantors,
reiterated "the willingness of the guarantor countries to
contribute in the present circumstances" to the efforts.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said the guarantors' proposal would include "the
agreements reached by Ecuador and Peru, and a formula for the
settlement of the matters still pending in relation to the marking
in the common border."
</P>
<P>
The proposal is expected to be submitted to the Ibero-American
Summit to be held on October 17 and 18 in Oporto, Portugal, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem and Chilean President Eduardo
Frei will also attend that meeting.
</P>
<P>
Quito and Lima have agreed on a treaty of trade and navigation
in the Amazons River, joint efforts in defending border
integration, the use of a waterway in the Zarumilla River, and
measures to resume mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
However, they are still bogged down in the border delimitation
dispute, especially in the El Condor mountain range, southeast of
Ecuador, the site of 1981 and 1995 armed conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
