<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Former Interim President Put Under Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadoran Anti-Corruption
Committee has started investigations on former Interim President
Fabian Alarcon and some officials on possible misconduct, reports
here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a recent clearance of accounts, the Ecuadoran government
found that several huge amounts of extra-budgetary funds were
appropriated during the administration of the former interim
government from January 1997 to July 1998.
</P>
<P>
The funds, which totaled more than 940 million U.S. dollars,
were not earmarked for the national priority projects despite
their dire needs of investment, but for some local projects.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ministry of Finance said all the above
expenditures were endorsed by Alarcon in person and implemented by
former Finance Minister Marco Flores.
</P>
<P>
None of the funds were used according to legal proceedings in
that no receipts or detailed accounts were available for most of
them, the report said. Explanations that were available for
certain funds, however, were not clearly worded.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Corruption Committee has filed the case for
investigation and issed a summon to Alarcon demanding that he
account for his decision on the disbursements, its justification
and legality as well as their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in response to requests of some members of
parliament, the Ecuadoran National Parliamentary Investigation
Committee has decided to start its investigation on the case.
</P>
<P>
The committee has notified Alarcon to get ready for queries by
members of parliament when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Observers have noticed that the extra-budgetary funds allegedly
appropriated by the former interim government accounted for 60
percent of the total deficits of the Ecuadoran government, which
stand at 1.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
If the allegations were confirmed, Alarcon will be sentenced on
charges of abuse of power and embezzlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
