<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 Thai MPs Expelled From Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Citizens Party (TCP)
has expelled 12 MPs who joined the Democrat-led coalition in
defiance of the party's resolution against participating in the
government, the Nation newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The move, taken on Saturday, effectively ended a protracted
feud that at times threatened to undermine the stability of the
coalition government, led by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
The 12 MPs defected from the TCP almost a year ago to join the
coalition in a move that irritated the TCP which bans its members
from participating in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion leaves the TCP with only five Parliament seats,
the second smallest party in the House.
</P>
<P>
TCP leader Samak Sundaravej had engineered the expulsion with
the intention to topple the coalition, since the move would strip
the defectors of their MP status, leading to the coalition to lose
its majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
But the expulsion came too late since Chuan boosted the
majority of his coalition by bringing in the National Development
Party last week, making the expulsion irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
The TCP said the defectors had disobeyed an earlier party
resolution against joining the coalition because they wanted
Cabinet positions and other political favors they were promised by
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Although it was almost certain that the renegades would lose
their MP status, some legal experts said that under the new
Constitution, they had the right to join another party to keep
their parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
The renegades told a press conference after leaving the TCP
headquarters following the expulsion vote that they would appeal
to the Constitution Court.
</P>
<P>
They questioned the procedure leading to their expulsion,
saying the party charter required that the executive committee
cast a confidential vote whereas Samak who chaired the meeting had
asked it to vote openly.
</P>
<P>
The renegades voiced doubt that all of the 54 votes in favor of
their expulsion had been cast by executive members present at the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Repays 2.19 Billion U.S. Dollars in Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela repaid 2.19 billion
U.S. dollars in the first nine months of this year, accounting for
8.76 percent of its total foreign debt, the Central Bank of
Venezuela said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the country's foreign exchange reserves
dropped by 4.7 billion dollars in the period, of which 2.19
billion were used for the repayment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the country's foreign debt climbed to 25
billion dollars and its foreign reserves to a record of 17.82
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government plans to repay 3.83 billion dollars
in foreign debt this year, of which two billion are the principle,
said Director of Coordination and Planning Office for the
Presidency Teodoro Petkoff.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this, the government needs to use 1.64 billion
dollars of its foreign reserves in the fourth quarter of this
year, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
