<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Int'l Contractor to Enhance Risk Control Means </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China's overseas businesses are
improving their edge in risk control to reduce the impact of
Southeast Asia's financial turmoil on their business, according to
today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"We have strengthened risk management to hedge against risks to
our operations," said Wang Zhendong, president of overseas
operation of the China State Construction Engineering Corp
(CSCEC), China's largest contractor.
</P>
<P>
Contracts claimed by overseas operations this year have fallen
slightly compared with the same period last year due to the slack
international market. However, the turnover will be between 1.8
billion U.S. dollars and 2 billion dollars, possibly making a new
record, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"We try to set proper bidding prices and ask project owners to
use U.S. dollars as currency to settle accounts if possible," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Many of CSCEC's overseas contracts are "turn-key" projects
involving design and construction, which means a wider profit
margin. Its leaner operation and higher efficiency have also
helped to lower the cost.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months this year, CSCEC received 20 foreign
orders each exceeding 10 million U.S. dollars, of which 15 came
from Asian nations and regions which totalled 1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that we will agree contracts worth 100 million
dollars in North Africa and 30 million dollars in South Africa
this year," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Based on global sales of 4.4 billion dollars, CSCEC was ranked
21st in 1997 among 225 international contractors by the
U.S. Engineering News Record Magazine.
</P>
<P>
However, challenges remains ahead. "Feeble economies in some
Asian nations, high technology content of projects and
protectionism exercised by some foreign countries are requiring
Chinese contractors to deepen corporate reform," said Gao Hucheng,
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The central government is ready to extend more loan quotas to
contractors and increase the tax rebate rates for equipment to
bolster the sector's growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
