<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Considers Plans to Transfer Surplus Capacity Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China is drafting a plan that
will encourage sectors suffering from overcapacity to transfer
production abroad, "Business Weekly" of "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
A list covering dozens of products from the light industry,
electronics and machinery sectors is being prepared, the newspaper
quoted an official with the State Economic and Trade Commission as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The commission, in collaboration with other government
agencies, is mulling measures to give companies in these sectors
incentives to make investment overseas, said the official without
elaborating more details.
</P>
<P>
But he said the measures would be integrated with the country's
efforts to upgrade its industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
China's industrial sector has been plagued by redundant
construction, which has resulted in widespread undercutting on the
domestic market and hence calls for setting price floors and
punishment for enterprises that sell their products at lower
prices.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that nearly 500 kinds of products are
manufactured at less than 60 percent of capacity. A large
proportion of those products have technological content and
quality better than similar goods in many developing
countries. Compared with those of developed countries, these
products also have considerable price advantages.
</P>
<P>
There is great potential for these products in international
market, said Xing Houyuan, a trade expert specializing in Chinese
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
According to her, China can transfer its technologically mature
industries to developing countries in the Middle East, the Gulf
Region, Latin America, Africa and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese enterprises, such Qingdao-based Haier Group and
Shanghai Radio and TV Co. Ltd., have already made some progress in
this direction.
</P>
<P>
By now, Chinese companies have invested six billion
U.S. dollars in setting up 6,000 business undertakings in 140
countries and regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
