<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders Deployment for Possible Kosovo Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has ordered the deployment of six B-52 bombers, one
reconnaissance aircraft and 13 tankers to Britain on Saturday for
possible air strikes in Kosovo, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The planes will be among 260 U.S. aircraft already committed by
the United States to support actions by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) against Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
Most of the force is already in Europe, either stationed at
bases or aboard the aircraft carrier Dwight D. Eisenhower, which
is currently in the Mediterranean Sea, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon statement announcing the deployment reiterated the
U.S. threat that if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic fails to
meet with the U.N. demands, "NATO has plans to use force to gain
his compliance by using air strikes that will damage his ability
to conduct military operations."
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who is on a tour in the Gulf region, told a news
conference in the Qatari capital Doha that the B-52s were being
moved so that, if NATO issued an "activation order" in the next
few days, those aircraft could be available for NATO European
commander to use "should he deem it necessary to do so." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
