<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tarim Basin to Fuel China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A string of recent exploration
breakthroughs in the Tarim Basin suggest that the colossal desert
area in northwest China will become the country's most significant
source of energy supplies in the next century, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The China National Star Petroleum Corp (CNSPC) has recently
announced its discovery of an oilfield with geological reserves
(proven reserves and controlled reserves combined) of over 100
million tons in the Tarim Basin, in northwest China's Uyger
autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
The Tahe Oilfield is located in the Shaya Uplift of the
northern Tarim Basin. Experts attribute the discovery to the new
approaches to explorations applied by the CNSPC.
</P>
<P>
Several international oil giants have contacted the CNSPC and
showed great interest in launching cooperation in the Tarim Basin
since the company's remarkable discovery was publicized, according
to the CNSPC.
</P>
<P>
The China National Petroleum Corp(CNPC), the country's flagship
oil company, has also made several significant findings in the
Tarim Basin recently, according to liang Digang, a ranking
official in the CNPC.
</P>
<P>
A high-yielding gas well named Kela-2 was drilled by the CNPC
in the Kuqa Depression in the northern Tarim Basin. With an oil-
and gas-bearing area of over 40 square kilometres, the Kela-2 gas
field will become the country's largest, with reserves expected to
be over 160 billion cubic metres, liang said.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that over 500 billion cubic metres of natural
gas will be proven in the basin by 2005," he added.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC has also found large amounts of oil resources last
year. The total geological reserves on the northern slope of the
Tazhong Uplift are estimated at over 100 million tons of crude
oil, and the oil reserves in the Lunnan area are also expected to
be over 100 million tons, Liang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0149 </DOCNO>
