<HEADLINE> Tourists Flock to Mount Wutai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Mount Wutai, a famous Buddhist
shrine in north China's Shanxi Province, hosted 525,000 domestic
and foreign tourists in the first eight months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The figure included 5,000 foreign tourists. The rising number
of visitors increased tourism earnings by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
The local government has not only intensified tourism
promotions both at home and abroad since the first day of the year,
but has also continued an extensive effort to improve
infrastructure. Rising tourism figures readily showed the effectiveness
of related efforts.
</P>
<P>
The local area hosted 3,156 foreign tourists during the Ninth
International Tourism Month from July 25 to August 25, up 15.8
percent on the previous year's period.
</P>
<P>
Mount Wutai, one of China's four sacred Buddhist mountains, is
home to 47 temples, the oldest of which dates back to Tang Dynasty
(618-907).
</P>
<P>
Wutai hosted a total of 600,000 tourists during 1997, with
earnings of 145 million yuan (18 million US dollars) representing
a 20 percent rise on the previous year's period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
