<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Chinese TV Tube Plant Enjoys Rising Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China's leading color television
tube producer has weathered the financial crisis sweeping
Southeast Asia and enjoyed soaring exports for the first nine
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Caihong Color Television Tube Plant located in Xianyang,
Shaanxi Province, produced 4 .79 million units during the
period. Total period sales of 5.37 million units, including units
in inventory, earned profits of 120 million yuan (14.46 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The plant, the largest of its kind in China, exported 1.31
million 37-cm tubes, up 22 percent on the previous year's
period. The company also exported 58,500 54-cm tubes, a dramatic
period rise of 400 percent.
</P>
<P>
The plant, China's first television tube manufacturer which
entered operations in the early 1980s, features a state-of-the-art
assembly produced in Japan. Caihong, which ranks first amongst 10
major Chinese television tube producers, has an annual production
capacity of seven million units. The company currently holds a 30
percent share of the domestic market and exports some 33 percent
of total output.
</P>
<P>
However, Caihong has faced severe challenges resulting from the
saturated domestic and international markets, with the worldwide
oversupply reaching 50 million units, including 10 million units
in China alone, and the unit price dropping by as much as 50
percent. The financial crisis in Southeast Asia has further
exacerbated the situation.
</P>
<P>
The company has cut costs to overcome difficulties, with costs
for the first nine months alone falling by 21.2 percent on the
1997 period. The effective program has greatly sharpened the
company's competitive edge. Caihong has also maintained
traditional markets such as Turkey and Hong Kong, and plans to
expand new markets in East Europe and Africa.
</P>
<P>
Caihong's January-September export earnings hit 44 million US
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey and Wales Make Shocks at European Qualifiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Wales made stunning
appearances at the European Soccer Championships qualifiers on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent reigning European champions Germany crashing to a
1-0 defeat in their group three qualifier in Bursa to underline
the deep-rooted problems currently afflicting the German national
side.
</P>
<P>
The other major upset of the night was in Copenhagen where
beleaguered Wales, without star forward Ryan Giggs, were
thoroughly overwhelmed by Denmark for almost their entire group
one match -- but won 2-1 thanks to a superb header four minutes
from time by 19-year-old substitute Craig Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
Those defeats for the last two nations to have been crowned
champions of Europe threw their respective groups wide open --
and put added pressure on new German coach Erich Ribbek and
Danish coach Bo Johannson to get it right when their sides play
Moldova and Switzerland respectively on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Johansson summed up the feelings of a coach who has just
experienced his side do everything but fail to win when he said
afterwards: "It's a nightmare -- but that's life."
</P>
<P>
Turkey, who beat Northern Ireland in their opening group three
match five weeks ago, went to the top of the group thanks to a
header by Hakan Sukur who punished some poor goalkeeping by
Oliver Kahn after 69 minutes of Germany's first qualifying match.
</P>
<P>
Ribbeck, who took over from Berti Vogts as coach last month,
quickly needs to get some injured players fit again -- and build
a new team following the retirement or the fading away of many of
Vogts's old stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
Wales, who lost 2-0 at home to Italy in their opener and have
had a miserable time over the last few years, looked to be
heading to another defeat when Soren Frederiksen put Denmark
ahead after 58 minutes.
</P>
<P>
But they were level through Adrian Williams a minute later
after a goalkeeping blunder by Peter Schmeichel's stand-in Mogens
Krogh -- although Krogh was powerless to stop Bellamy's winning
header close to the end.
</P>
<P>
While those former champions were losing, France showed the
true grit expected of world champions when they came back to beat
Russia 3-2 in Moscow in group four qualifier after letting a
two-goal lead slip from their grasp.
</P>
<P>
France secured their first victory since beating Brazil in the
World Cup Final in July when Alain Boghossian scored the winner
eight minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Nicolas Anelka (13) and Robert Pires (29) got France away to a
superb start, but Russia rallied with goals from Igor
Yanovsky(45) and Alexander Mostovoi (57) before Boghossian scored
the winner.
</P>
<P>
France could have won by an even bigger margin if Laurent
Blanc had not driven a late penalty against the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
The victory was hugely welcome for the French following a draw
with Iceland in their opening match, but Russia now face a tough
task to qualify after losing both their opening matches to
Ukraine and now France.
</P>
<P>
Croatia, who reached the semi-finals of the World Cup in the
summer, also needed to dig deep into their reserves to overcome a
shock half-time deficit against Malta before winning 4-1.
</P>
<P>
Scotland also showed some rare tenacity by twice coming from
behind to defeat Estonia 3-2 -- but England, hosts of the 1996
European championships and expected to reach the finals again in
2000 had a poor day, being held to a 0-0 drab home draw by
Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
For a while it looked as though Malta were going to pull off a
real upset in Valletta against Croatia in their group eight match
after Hubert Suda put them ahead with a 28th minute penalty.
</P>
<P>
Malta played some attractive football, but eventually were
overrun by the superior Croats who scored through Davor Vugovic
(2), Dario Simic and Davor Suker, the World Cup's top scorer.
</P>
<P>
Scotland ended the worst run of matches without a win in their
international history when they twice came from behind to defeat
Estonia 3-2 in a group nine qualifier at Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
While Scotland were exalting in a rare victory, their
arch-foes England were playing poorly in a 0-0 draw with Bulgaria
at Wembley.
</P>
<P>
After losing their opening group five match 2-1 in Sweden,
England now face an uphill battle to qualify for the finals in
2000. The result increases the pressure on England coach Glenn
Hoddle, but also did not help Bulgaria's cause much as they also
lost their opening game, 3-0 to Poland last month.
</P>
<P>
However there was also a notable performance by Latvia, who
maintained their 100 percent start in group two with a 1-0 win
over Georgia to ensure they remain in top position in group two.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, however, who stunned Spain 3-2 in their first
game,were brought back to earth by Austria who won with two goals
by Harald Cerny and one from Hannes Reinmayr. 
</P>
</TEXT>
