<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Sees Political Settlement Possible for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav authorities said
Sunday that the talks between President Slobodan Milosevic and
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke has made a political settlement for
the Kosovo crisis possible.
</P>
<P>
A statement released through the Tanjug news agency following
Holbrooke and Milosevic's seven-hour talks said: "It was agreed
that all necessary conditions exist for the resolution of open
questions through a political process."
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "The demands contained in the U.N. Security
Council Resolution have been realized in practice, which is
evidenced by the accelerated normalization of the situation in the
field."
</P>
<P>
However, there was no immediate comment from Holbrooke on the
statement or the outcome of the talks in a last-ditch effort to
avert a military attack threatened by NATO on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The talks ended after Washington announced its dispatch of B-52
bombers to Britain for a possible attack on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
