<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav authorities said Sunday that the talks
between President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke has made a political settlement for the Kosovo crisis
possible.
</P>
<P>
A statement released through the Tanjug news agency following
Holbrooke and Milosevic's seven-hour talks said: "It was agreed
that all necessary conditions exist for the resolution of open
questions through a political process." (Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Defense Secretary George Robertson said
Saturday the stationing of six U.S. B-52 bombers on its soil
showed that NATO meant business in preparing possible Kosovo air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen has ordered the bombers to
be sent from the United States to Britain in readiness for
possible military intervention in Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
(UK-US-Bombers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- A Congolese airliner was shot down by rebels in the
east of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) Saturday as it
headed for Kinshasa, the capital city in the southwest of the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted Congolese Information Minister Didier Mumengi
as saying the plane was brought down when it took off from Kindu,
where government army and rebels fighting to oust President
Laurent Kabila have been contending for its control.
(Congo (K)-Downing of Plane)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent made a call
on Saturday for an early lifting of the eight-year-old
U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He made the call at a meeting with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz which focused on Aziz's recent meetings with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and other U.N. officials in New
York. (Jordan-Aziz)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The Albanian government on Saturday said that if NATO
decided to launch military strikes against Yugoslavia over Kosovo,
its forces could go across the Albanian territorial air and waters
for the attack.
</P>
<P>
An Albanian government spokesman said that the plan was
approved by Albanian government Saturday. (Albania-NATO-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov warned
Saturday that the use of force by NATO in Kosovo could lead to the
revision of relations between Russia and the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Primakov reiterated Moscow's resolve to veto any U.N.
resolution authorizing NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot allow this resolution," the Interfax news agency
quoted Primakov as saying. (Russia-Kosovo) 
</P>
