<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Defense Chief on Stationing of U.S. Bombers in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said Saturday night that the stationing of six U.S. B-52
bombers on its soil showed that NATO meant business in preparing
possible Kosovo air strikes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen has ordered the bombers to
be sent from the United States to Britain in readiness for
possible military intervention in Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, whose country is in favor of military actions in
resolving the Kosovo crisis, was quoted by Reuters as saying,
"This is a further demonstration that NATO means business."
</P>
<P>
"We hope for a diplomatic solution, but (Yugoslav President
Slobodan) Milosevic should take note of the seriousness of our
resolve," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bombers were scheduled to leave Barksdale air force
base in Louisiana, the United States, at 7 pm local time (midnight
GMT) Saturday for Fairford air force base, about 75 miles (120km)
west of London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
