<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Urges Setting Up of Global Credit Rating System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair called on the Group of Seven (G7) major industrialized
nations to set up a world "credit rating" system.
</P>
<P>
Blair, whose country is holding the current G7 presidency, told
Britain's Sunday Business newspaper, "What we need is a set of
clear standards that countries sign up to. It's almost like a
credit rating that they have in the international finance system."
</P>
<P>
"Then everyone knows what they are dealing with and they go
into it with their eyes open, recognizing that countries that
don't have those types of open financial systems are countries
that are more risky to do business with," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, due to be published Sunday, said Blair hoped
that countries would agree to an international code on openness
and transparency at a G7 summit on the global economic crisis to
be held in London later this year.
</P>
<P>
The G7 country comprises the United States, Canada, Britain,
France Italy, Germany and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
