<DOCNO> XIE19981011.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy to Grow by 2 Percent, Says S.F. Fed Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A Federal Reserve Bank
official said U.S. economic growth next year is likely to be "just
under 2 percent," San Francisco Chronicle reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
San Francisco Fed chief Robert Parry said Friday that recent
stock market declines and rising interest rates charged to riskier
borrowers "could put sizable damper" on consumer and business
spending. But disputing suggestions that the United States might
be heading for a recession, he expected slow growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
By rising interest rates, Parry referred to a sudden major leap
in mortgage rates in this country, nearly a full percentage point
in just the past few days.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the week, American homeowners could have
secured an interest rate as low as 7.25 percent on a 30-year,
fixed-rate no-points conforming loan. Now the rate would be 8.125
percent. On a 200,000-dollar loan, this week's rate increase would
add a 120-dollar per month to the mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the spike to a surge in U.S. Treasury bond
rates, caused by the dollar's fall against the yen. They do not
expect rates to stay high long, given the soft economy worldwide
and the overall trend toward lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Parry gave no clear signal whether the Fed is likely to reduce
interest rates beyond the quarter-percent cut in the federal funds
rate announced last week. The Chronicle quoted him as saying that
"it's too early to speculate" and "one has to allow some time to
determine if that move is sufficient." 
</P>
</TEXT>
