<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Expects IMF to Resume Aid Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Finance Minister
Simeon Nyachae has said he was "more than confident" that the
suspended aid loans from the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
will be restored early next year.
</P>
<P>
An IMF team will visit Kenya in December for talks on resuming
the three-year 205-million-U.S.-Dollar aid program, he was quoted
by a media report reaching here Saturday from London.
</P>
<P>
By early December this year, any remaining barriers to the
concerned talks will be removed and funding could resume as soon
as early 1999, he told the Financial Times newspaper in London
Friday after attending this week's annual meetings of the IMF and
the World Bank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed on how to go about the outstanding issues. We
believe the remaining matters will be sorted out between now and
early December at the latest," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if fresh funds might be disbursed as early as the first
quarter of 1999, Nyachae replied: "A lot of things have already
been done behind the scenes. I am more than confident of what you
are estimating."
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended the aid package in July 1997, only one year
into the three-year program, citing corruption and poor
governance in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said three months ago that Kenya still had to fulfill
two key conditions before it would start negotiations to restart
the program, a concessional loan package designed for some of the
world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
The remaining conditions were to strengthen the independence
of the country's official Anti-Corruption Authority, set up last
year, and to establish accountability in the so-called Goldenberg
fraud scandal.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae said the government was preparing new regulations to
ensure that members of the Anti-Corruption Authority were
nominated by professional bodies and civil groups, including
legal, business and banking associations, rather than by
President Daniel arap Moi or other political figures.
</P>
<P>
More steps would have to be taken to ensure that corruption
was seen to be effectively punished, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Moi suspended the authority's boss, John Harun Mwau, in July
after Mwau's accusations of fraud against four senior Treasury
officials sparked a war of words with Nyachae. 
</P>
</TEXT>
